The expected rise results from an improved outlook for global tourism. BANGKOK - Thailand expects revenue from foreign tourists to rise 8.5 percent to 1.78 trillion baht ($49.8 billion) this year, a deputy prime minister said on Monday.The expected rise results from an improved outlook for global tourism as well as Thailand's investment in infrastructure, Deputy Prime Minister Thanasak Patimaprakorn told reporters.&quot;This is another year that we will need to focus on quality tourism more than tourist numbers,&quot; he said.Thanasak expects daily tourist spending to increase to 5,200 baht per person this year, from 5,100 baht last year. Last year, Thailand had 32.6 million visitors, a rise of nearly 9 percent from the year before.